Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888800022&r=1&w=2">Re:  leading digits in domain names</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837783700007&r=1&w=2">Dave Johnson &lt;dbj () rice ! edu&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198704">1987-04-24 0:02:01</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926856&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926856&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Technically, there is no difference between a "host name" and a "domain
name".  For example, RICE.EDU is both a SUN-2/120 running UNIX and
the name of our domain.  The only thing that makes a node in the domain
tree a host is the presence of A records, but this doesn't make it
not a domain too, since that node can still have descendants in the
tree.  Thus, even though RICE.EDU has an A record, it also has
nodes with other A records below it for TITAN.RICE.EDU, IAPETUS.RICE.EDU,
etc.

Also, making special exceptions for machines that aren't on the Internet
is a bad idea since they may someday become connected to the Internet.
It would be silly to need to change the name if the machine suddenly
got connected to the rest of the Internet.  That's as bad as needing
to change from something.UUCP to something.EDU (or whatever) when
you get connected to the Internet.

I think labels in the domain tree should be allowed to begin with a
digit.  It's already done with IN-ADDR.ARPA, so it's already a little
late to restrict such things elsewhere in the domain tree, such as for
labels under .COM.

                                        Dave

